    <text>
        <body><div type="bibliography">
                
                <p><bibl><ptr target="#marengo2010a"/>, p. 152, n.<citedRange>18</citedRange>, fig. 3, 18</bibl>;
                    <bibl><ptr target="#IGCyr"/> <citedRange>112660</citedRange></bibl>.</p>
            </div><div type="edition" xml:lang="grc" xml:space="preserve">
                
                <ab>
                    <lb n="1"/><orig>νι</orig>
                </ab>
            </div><div type="apparatus" xml:space="preserve">
            
                <p>
                    <app loc="1">
                            <rdg resp="#marengo2010a"><orig>νι</orig> <note>left-to-right, if read from the centre</note></rdg>
                            <rdg resp="#marengo2010a"><orig>ιν</orig> <note>right-to-left, if read from outside</note></rdg>
                    </app>
                </p>
               </div><div type="translation" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="fr">
                <p>Intraduisible.</p>
            </div><div type="translation" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="en">
                <p>Not usefully translatable.</p>
            </div><div type="translation" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="it">
                <p>Intraducibile.</p>
            </div><div type="translation" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="ar">
            <p>غير قابل للترجمة بشكل جيد</p>
         </div><div type="commentary">
                
                <p>Due to the date of the ceramics and the shape of letter nu, a right-to-left reading seems less plausible than the left-to-right one, which 
                    we choose to edit. However this remains an undecided question for trademark of type 15B at <bibl><ptr target="#johnston1979"/>, pp. <citedRange>104, 198</citedRange></bibl>
                and <bibl><ptr target="#johnston2006"/>, pp. <citedRange>84-85</citedRange></bibl>.
                </p>
            </div></body>
    </text>
